{
  "texts": [
    "Pakes and Griliches (1980) introduced the idea of a \"knowledge production function\" (\"KPF\") that has become, either explicitly or implicitly, the measurement framework at the base of most microeconometric studies of innovation.",
    "It posits a functional relationship between inputs to knowledge generation (e.g.",
    "previously existing knowledge and firm expenditure on research) and the creation of new knowledge.",
    "This stock of knowledge is an important variable in most models of endogenous growth, playing a similar role to physical capital in the neoclassical growth model (e.g., Romer, 1990; Aghion and Howitt, 1992).",
    "But how do we measure new knowledge?"
  ]
}